# Gitmoji Commits

Use **Gitmoji** for every git commit in this repo. Put **one emoji at the start** of the subject line, then a short English description.

Format: `<emoji> <imperative description>`

## Emoji guide (this project)

| Emoji | Use when |
|-------|----------|
| ✨ | New feature (store, bot command, API endpoint, gateway) |
| 🐛 | Bug fix |
| 📝 | README or docs only |
| 📄 | `.env.example`, config, sample files |
| 🌐 | i18n / translations (`translations.json`, locale) |
| ♻️ | Refactor without behavior change |
| ⚡ | Performance improvement |
| 🔒 | Security (auth, CSRF, JWT, rate limits, integrity) |
| 👷 | CI/CD, Docker, GitHub Actions, deploy scripts |
| 🔖 | Release / version bump |
| ⬆️ | Dependency or package upgrade |
| 🎨 | UI / styling (AdminUi, StoreUi, themes) |
| 🗃️ | Database schema or migration |
| 🔧 | Tooling (`tools/`, scripts) |
| 🚑 | Critical hotfix |
| 🗑️ | Remove code or files |

## Examples

```
✨ Add PayPal subscription renewal
🐛 Fix Telegram webhook duplicate updates
🌐 Add Arabic bot command texts
🔒 Harden admin 2FA rate limiting
👷 Add GitHub release workflow
📝 Update README installation steps
```

## Rules

- One emoji per commit; no emoji at the end
- Keep subject under ~72 characters
- Use English for commit subjects
- Pick the **most specific** emoji; prefer 🐛 over ✨ for fixes
